results.notes: An interesting fungi which appears each year on dead wood often on moss covered wood. It has the strange ability to turn the substrate black including the moss upon which it grows. results.notes:
One of multiple flushing sections of a Lacey, WA construction site that I have been monitoring and anticipating(Morchella) since last summer(2018). This phenomenon is one of the proof positives for urban morels(especially M. importuna). If you see a large development or construction site during summer months, make a note of it and return in early May(at least here in Western Washington State). The likelihood for M. importuna with this method is always high. Not a given, but a good rule of thumb if you can’t get up to the mountains for naturals(e.g. Morchella snyderi). I harvested one fruiting body from each of the four photographed locations here today(for dehydration/herbarium collection and voucher). I also returned later in the day and found another half pound on an adjacent strip of grass/cement(all harvests/fruiting spots within a few feet of lamp posts).
Ladder like pits with grooved notch to stipe=fieldmark for M. importuna(along with construction site, disturbed, landscape, cement edged habitat).

results.notes:
Three to four separate patches found in a sandy, riparian zone near Santa Fe. Elevation ~7,500-7,800 feet. They are not as abundant as morels in the Elata clade in the area. Habitat is thin and scarce. I’ve only found about 8 of these, whereas I’ve found ~400-500 M. snyderi and M. elata clade morels (M. brunnea, maybe). I want to say these were growing near an Ash but tree identification is an ongoing process for me. Someone please chime in. They seem to only grow with trees of a certain age as well. Can’t find them around any of the bigger trees of the same species. Small groves of young trees with leaf litter and sand seems to be their preferred habitat. These photos are three to four separate patches, with one patch producing five specimens and the others only producing one each. Dried leaves, sand, near a river, and identical trees of a certain age are what all these patches had in common.

I had read somewhere that M. americana doesn’t grow above 5,000 feet elevation. I was surprised to find these but happy to add a data point at this elevation. If anyone has any literature on the elevation range of M. americana, I would appreciate that information too.

Exact location has been left off because of the scarcity of the habitat here. Anyone familiar with the tree species and the Santa Fe area can probably determine where it is with a little effort.

results.notes:
Fruiting body of 20 caps joined in a single stipe, overall 30cm X 16cm X 16cm. Individual caps to 11cm W, rising from off-center fleshy stalks fanning upward and out in a curving shape. Inrolled edges. Caps grey-tan and velvety. Pore surface white and smooth w/ fine pores. White spores. Flesh white, nonstaining, uniform, firm but flexible and somewhat brittle. Stipe 14cm across, apparently growing from a degraded maple log. Odor mild, mushroomy. Taste mild. Taste—cooked—rich, savory with slight bitter after taste. Specimen persisted for 3 weeks, with little degrading.
Riparian habitat with hardwoods and redwood. July 1 fruiting time unusual in our neighborhood. 100" rain the winter before. Only 1 specimen found. Have not seen another, before or since.
